<li id="cite_note-125"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Hanukkah#cite_ref-125">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFLebowitz2005" class="citation magazine">Lebowitz, Rabbi Aryeh (11 December 2005). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://download.yutorah.org/2015/1083/846556/d-varim-hayotzim-min-halev-miketz.pdf">"Chanukah Gelt and Gifts"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. <i>Dvarim Hayotzim Min Halev</i> (PDF). Vol.&#160;17 no.&#160;6. p.&#160;3<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">6 October</span> 2018</span>. <q>In fact, the Orchos Rabeinu in cheilek ג teaches that the Steipler Gaon maintained the minhag of giving out Chanukah gelt davka on the fifth night of Chanukah. Why specifically the fifth night? Answers the Orchos Rabeinu, since the fifth night is the only night that cannot coincide with Shabbos.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Dvarim+Hayotzim+Min+Halev&amp;rft.atitle=Chanukah+Gelt+and+Gifts&amp;rft.volume=17&amp;rft.issue=6&amp;rft.pages=3&amp;rft.date=2005-12-11&amp;rft.aulast=Lebowitz&amp;rft.aufirst=Rabbi+Aryeh&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdownload.yutorah.org%2F2015%2F1083%2F846556%2Fd-varim-hayotzim-min-halev-miketz.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHanukkah" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
